@gianm this issue is more about usability than is being possible to do something. Neither what I am proposing here nor #2433 unlock any functionality that is otherwise impossible to achieve. 

Look at this through the eyes of a new Druid user: the JS post agg getting unfinalized values is simply useless. There is literally no scenario where you would want that.

Consider:

``` json
{
  "queryType": "timeseries",
  "dataSource": "wikipedia",
  "granularity": "all",
  "intervals": [
    "2016-02-01/2016-02-05"
  ],
  "aggregations": [
    {
      "fieldNames": [
        "page"
      ],
      "name": "NumPages",
      "type": "cardinality"
    }
  ],
  "postAggregations": [
    {
      "type": "javascript",
      "name": "NumPagesMod1337",
      "fieldNames": [
        "NumPages"
      ],
      "function": "function(NumPages) { return typeof NumPages === 'number' }"
    }
  ]
}
```

It gives back: 

``` json
{
  "error" : "Invalid JavaScript value of type io.druid.query.aggregation.hyperloglog.HLLCV1 (fn#1)"
}
```

`NumPages` in being passed in a way that can not even be used by the JS language.

As such it would be an improvement to the **usability** of the Druid query API if the inputs to a JS port agg were auto finalized for you. That is what my issue is about at it's core.

